important_segment: During September there was a temporal trend toward greater support for Democratic than Republican candidates, b = −0.08, 95% confidence interval (CI) = [−0.096, −0.057], but this pattern was reversed during October, when there was a temporal trend toward greater support for Republican than Democratic candidates, b = 0.07, 95% CI = [0.063, 0.084]. important_segment: Beta weights corresponding to blood-oxygen-level-dependent (BOLD) signals were extracted from the right amygdala. important_segment: An F test of the percentage of time participants in Experiment 3 agreed to run the filter with condition (positive, negative, or neutral prime) as the independent variable yielded a significant effect of condition. important_segment: Supporting the authors' argument, senators appear to have strategically changed whether they mentioned pro-immigration actions in their explanations depending on the constituents' position. When receiving a pro-immigration letter from a constituent, 23.2% of letters mentioned reinforcing or compensating pro-immigration actions. This was nearly double the 12.5% of letters that mentioned pro-immigration actions in response to anti-immigration letters (p = 0.07 [two-tailed], based on the exact McNemar significance probability).

important_segment: The coefficient on occupational status of time since the birth of the first child is statistically significant and negative (−.112, p < 0.05) indicating that occupational status does not rebound as a child grows older. In fact, if higher-order births are controlled, the first birth penalty increases as a child grows older. With each year since the first birth, the mother is penalized an extra .112 status points in addition to the .394 penalty around the birth itself.

important_segment: The analysis is based on an experiment implemented in a coeducational public middle school in Jiangsu, China. In the experiment, a research group in the local Department of Education randomly assigned students’ seats with input from the authors. The assignment procedure involved first nonrandomly assigning a small number of students and then randomly assigning the remaining students to the remaining seats. The data for this study consist of three rounds of test scores and two rounds of surveys for students of grade 7 in fall 2009. The baseline test and baseline survey were administrated during the first week of the semester before random seat assignment. Given the within-block randomization of seats, the authors estimate the main effects of peers by regressing the mean standardized midterm and final scores for a student in a given block and class on the gender of the desk mate and surrounding neighbors, as well as all of the focal student's baseline characteristics (gender, baseline test score, height, age, birth order, mother’s and father’s education, and interest in Chinese, math, and English), an indicator for whether the focal student's desk mate is a favored student, and the share of favored students among the focal student's neighboring peers, along with block fixed effects. Statistical inference is performed using exact permutation tests. In the model selected as evidence for the SCORE program (Table 5, Panel B, Column 1), the model is estimated on the sample of female students and the effect of the desk mate and neighbor 4 students are combined.

important_segment: A 2 (focus on product information vs. feeling) × 2 (mind-set: abstract thinking vs. concrete thinking) × 2 (fluency: blurry advertisement vs. clear advertisement) ANOVA on the averaged liking ratings revealed a significant three-way interaction, F(1, 106) = 5.49, p = .02, partial eta squared = .05. Specifically, when participants were told to focus on the content of the advertisement, fluency increased liking in the concrete-thinking condition but had no effect in the abstract-thinking condition. However, when participants were told to focus on their feelings, the effect was reversed: Fluency increased liking in the abstract-thinking condition but had no effect in the concrete-thinking condition.

important_segment: The result as characterized by the author: "Figure 10 shows that income inequality has little or no significant impact on the segregation of the very poorest families of a metropolitan area from all other families but has large and significant effects on the segregation of moderate- to high-income families from those with lower incomes." The result obtained by the authors was b = .837, SE = .130, p < .001 (see Table C2).

important_segment: Results show that in the baseline condition, in which subjects participate in multiple rounds of the PGG without any type of interaction, contributions decline by almost 10%, in line with previous experiments. In contrast, when participants were allowed to communicate, there is a visible increase in contributions: on average, the contribution in the communication condition is 1.91 MUs higher (P < .001) than in the baseline condition. Repeated interaction supported by communication is therefore effective in triggering mechanisms of reciprocity and increases the overall level of co-operation

The estimated coefficient with industry-year and bank dummies is about 0.08, which means that when a firm’s bank suffers a 30% decline in its market-to-book value, the firm’s annual exports declined 2.7% relative to a firm whose bank’s health did not decline. The portion of this finding that is selected is column (3) of Table III (coefficient is 0.082, standard error of 0.018, significant at 1 percent level).

important_segment: Larger BFLPE (big-fish-little-pond) effects were associated with students who used memorization to a greater extent. Students in high-ability schools who used the memorization technique to a greater extent suffered a larger decline in mathematics self-concept than those who used the technique to a lesser extent. Although all students who used memorization had lower mathematics self-concepts if they attended high-ability schools than students of similar memorization usage who attended average- or low-ability schools, the drop in mathematics self-concept was more pronounced for students who used memorization to a greater extent.

important_segment: The information in Table 3 strongly contradicts Hypothesis 3, which maintains that leaders in majoritarian governments rarely use either SEI or PSI for diversionary purposes. important_segment: The hypothesis that information about relatively good performance raises citizens’ assessments of performance (H1 a) is supported. Consistent with this hypothesis, in the field, the mean perception of performance of citizens with information was 3.693 (standard deviation = 0.779) which was higher than those without information who had a mean of 3.326 (standard deviation = 0.794). The associated t-test of difference in mean performance assessment produced a positive value of t with p < .001 as shown in table 2 (from the 'Field' column of Table 2: t(349) = 4.372). The Cohen’s d measure shows that information about good performance raised citizens’ assessments by 0.468 (in the field) standard deviations of the performance assessment variable.

important_segment: The authors' statistical models show that good governance is crucial to reducing the risk of conflict recurrence. important_segment: Firms with a high share of imported inputs relative to total variable costs exhibit lower pass-through into destination-currency export prices - a 10  percentage point higher import intensity is associated with a 6  percentage point lower pass-through. A typical firm with zero import intensity has a pass-through of 87  percent (= 1 − 0.13), while a firm with a 38  percent import intensity (in the ninety-fifth percentile of the distribution) has a pass-through of only 64 percent (= 1 − 0.13 − 0.60 · 0.38). important_segment: Infants’ ability to predict the goal of manual actions directed toward the mouth (i.e. looking at the mouth area of interest prior to the tool reaching the actor’s mouth) varies dramatically between cultural contexts. Chinese infants fixate the mouth before food arrives there, if chopsticks are used to manipulate the food. If a typically Western-style spoon is used to manipulate the food, however, then Chinese infants fail to predict these events. Swedish infants demonstrate the opposite pattern of results, predicting that food being handled by a Western-style spoon will go to the mouth, but fail to predict the same goal when the action is per-formed with chopsticks.

important_segment: In this paper the authors use the “system GMM” [General Methods of Moments] approach developed by Arellano and Bond (1991) and Blundell and Bond (1998). A simultaneous equation system conveyed in equations 4-8 is employed for the estimation, where the outcome variable is the unit price of a variety i from country k in import market j and year t. The focal term is the price of China’s exports. Table 1 reports the estimated results for the whole sample. The selected results come from the analysis of middle-income countries (see 'P_Middle' column in Table 1 for details).

important_segment: The results for the contextual factors, especially the positive effect for sit-ins, are our most important findings. Though living in a county near a sit-in county did not significantly influence opinions about civil rights protest, living in a county where one occurred did. Specifically, controlling for individual-level and other contextual factors, the probability of white Southerners who lived in a sit-in county approving of the protest tactic was nearly three times that of those who resided in a county without or nearby a sit-in. (B = 1.091, SE = .520, OR = 2.977, p < .1)

important_segment: According to hypothesis 1a, the greater the appeal of a protest event’s claims, the more likely the protest’s participants will utilize nonviolent disruptive tactics. Model 2 in table 3 gives evidence in support of this assertion. Specifically, as the aggregate claim appeal of a protest event increases by one standard deviation, the odds of the protest using nonviolent disruptive tactics relative to only non-disruptive tactics rise by approximately 8 percent (exp(0.073) = 1.075, p < .001, model 2, table  3).

important_segment: The deviation between regional-level unemployment and the national trend — ‘structural component’ 2, which represents the typical regional situation — is significantly negative (from Table 2, Model 1, 'Component 2: Typical regional unemployment' term: AME [average marginal effect] = -0.003; clustered S.E. = 0.001; P < 0.05). The relatively clear impact of this component suggests that structural differences between regions are typically more relevant than the impact of de-trended unemployment (Component 3). This means that persistently high unemployment in one’s own living area decreases an individual’s chance of obtaining a dual training place. Hypothesis 4a can be confirmed.

important_segment: The authors' main goal is to investigate if the effect of the CFC program on student achievement will be mediated by changes in quality of text discussion. Since they are interested in student level outcomes, the mediator is at the teacher level, and random assignment occurred at the school level, they use a 3 -> 2 -> 1 mediation design (Pituch et al., 2010). To test the indirect effect, they followed the procedure described by Pituch et al. (2010). They constructed confidence intervals using the Sobel (1982) standard error (see p. 41). They used the PRODCLIN software program to test the significance of the indirect effect.

important_segment: The claim was tested by calculating the proportion of participants who met full, subsyndromal, or no PTSD at baseline, 3 months, and 12 months according to participants’ diagnostic or subsyndromal status. To determine the influence of resolved PTSD on subsequent WHOQOL  (World Health Organization Quality of Life measure) indices at 12 months, the authors identified participants who met at least subsyndromal PTSD at 3 months but did not meet subsyndromal level of PTSD at 12 month. Odds ratios (comparing to the No PTSD group) were adjusted for WHOQOL scores in the 2 weeks prior to traumatic injury, rated pain, and presence of major depression at 12 months. The portion of the claim selected is the effect of resolved PTSD on the psychological QoL scale | The claim was tested by calculating the proportion of participants who met full, subsyndromal, or no PTSD at baseline, 3 months, and 12 months according to participants’ diagnostic or subsyndromal status. To determine the influence of resolved PTSD on subsequent WHOQOL  (World Health Organization Quality of Life measure) indices at 12 months, the authors identified participants who met at least subsyndromal PTSD at 3 months but did not meet subsyndromal level of PTSD at 12 month. Odds ratios (comparing to the No PTSD group) were adjusted for WHOQOL scores in the 2 weeks prior to traumatic injury, rated pain, and presence of major depression at 12 months. important_segment: ...To allow more explicitly for potential forgetting, the authors estimate a specification that allows for knowledge depreciation over time. Specifically, they assume that experience is accumulated according to a perpetual-inventory process: E_t = delta(E_t-1 + q_t-1). Experience at the beginning of period t is a fraction 'delta' of the sum of two components: the experience at the start of the prior period and production in the prior period, q_t-1 . Thus delta parameterizes forgetting or, more precisely, retention. Nonlinear least squares estimates of the forgetting model are in column 3 of both panels. The weekly data is selected.
